`,htmlContent:""},{title:"What Are Intervals? (Beginner Level)",subtitle:"Hear distance â€” and copy melodies faster",lang:"en",slug:"intervals",order:2,status:"published",readingTime:"5min",updated:"2025-01-22",keywords:["intervals","ear training","guitar","music theory"],related:["theory-intro","chords"],sources:[],content:`
# ðŸŽ¼ What Are Intervals? (Beginner Level)

> **Intervals = the unit of distance between notes.**
> When you think in terms of how far sounds are from each other, ear training, songwriting, and analysis become much clearer.

---

## 1) Why knowing distances helps

When you learn a melody or riff by ear, you're already sensing **distance** without realizing it.
"Up a little," "down a lot" â€” that sense of movement can be described with **numbers**, and that's what intervals are for.
Once you know them, you can **recreate musical relationships** easily with numbers.

* **Ear training:** write down what you hear as distances.
* **Composition:** design melodic rises and drops to shape emotion.
* **Analysis:** describe chord progressions or melodies as measurable movements.

Intervals form the **foundation** for understanding **chords (harmony)** and **scales (pitch collections)** later on.

For example, the C major chord contains Câ€“Eâ€“G, and E major contains Eâ€“Gâ™¯â€“B. Remembering every chord by note is hardâ€”but interval thinking simplifies it.
A **major chord** always uses **root, 3rd, and 5th**.
If your root is C or Fâ™¯, just take the notes that are a 3rd and 5th above the rootâ€”that's your major chord.
With intervals, you can **build any chord logically**, no memorization required.

---

## 2) Câ€“Dâ€“Eâ€“Fâ€“Gâ€“Aâ€“Bâ€“C in intervals

Using the C major scale as an example:

| Note     | C   | D   | E   | F   | G   | A   | B   | C            |
| -------- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | ------------ |
| Interval | 1st | 2nd | 3rd | 4th | 5th | 6th | 7th | 8th (octave) |

"D" is two steps (a 2nd) above "C," and "E" is three steps (a 3rd) above.
The key point: **count the starting note (the root) as 1st.**

---

## 3) What's the root? The counting rule

When measuring intervals, always remember:

> **Count the starting note (the root) as the first one.**

If your root is C, you count Câ†’Dâ†’Eâ€¦ and so on.
If the root is D, the same shape (Dâ€“Eâ€“Fâ™¯â€“Gâ€“Aâ€“Bâ€“Câ™¯) shifts up a whole tone.

| Root   | 1st | 2nd | 3rd | 4th | 5th | 6th | 7th |
| ------ | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| C root | C   | D   | E   | F   | G   | A   | B   |
| D root | D   | E   | Fâ™¯  | G   | A   | B   | Câ™¯  |

They sound nearly the same, just **one whole tone higher** overall, because the **distances remain identical**.
That's why Câ€“Dâ€“Eâ€“Fâ€“Gâ€“Aâ€“Bâ€“C is simply "the pattern starting from C." Change the root, and you change the **key**.

---

## 4) Half steps and whole steps on guitar

Understanding **half steps** and **whole steps** is essential.
"Câ†’D" is a **whole step (2 frets)**, "Eâ†’F" is a **half step (1 fret)**.
This difference shapes the bright or tense feel of musicâ€”major vs. minor, resolution vs. tension.
The guitar is especially good at **visualizing intervals**: once you know the root, you can **see where the 2nd, 3rd, and other intervals** lie instantly on the fretboard.

---

## 5) Summary: Intervals are music's universal measurement

* **Intervals = distance between notes.** They're the foundation of ear training, composition, and improvisation.
* Thinking in **intervals instead of note names** helps you see structure consistently across all keys.
* The guitar makes intervals visibleâ€”knowing the root shows you where every other degree lies.
* Câ€“Dâ€“Eâ€“Fâ€“Gâ€“Aâ€“Bâ€“C is just one example based on the root C.
* Once you grasp intervals, music theory becomes much easier to see and hear.

> In the next article, you'll learn how these distances combine to form **chords (harmony)**.
> In the OtoTheory app, you can explore intervals visually through fretboards, chord dictionaries, and other toolsâ€”give it a try!`,htmlContent:""},{title:"What Is a Key?",subtitle:"Feel the gravity that holds music together",lang:"en",slug:"key-center",order:4,status:"published",readingTime:"4min",updated:"2025-01-22",keywords:["key","tonality","tonic","chord progression"],related:["theory-intro","chords","diatonic"],sources:[],content:`
